<DESCRIPT>  THEATER; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A Christmas Carol; (box)The original grinch,  Ebenezer Scrooge, finds the true
meaning of Christmas. A classic production.  Through Dec. 26. ACT at the
Orpheum Theater, San Francisco. (415) 749-2228.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NOW PLAYING  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  PERFORMANCE  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     City of Angels; (box)Film noir  detectives, tongue in cheek. This musical
won the 1990 Tony Award. (Reviewed by Murry Frymer.)  Through Jan. 5. Golden
Gate Theater, San Francisco. (408) 998-2277, (510) 762-2277.;   Fat Men in
Skirts; (box)Cannibalism and incest  are darkly funny in Nicky Silver's
brilliant, audacious play.  Through Jan. 26. Magic Theater, San Francisco.
(415) 441-8822.;   Just Say No; (box)A limp satire  on our (lack of a)
national AIDS policy, by gay activist Larry Kramer. Dated the day it was
written.  Extended through Dec. 23. Z Collective at Davies Medical Center, San
Francisco. (415) 666-2317.;   The Middle Ages; (box)Some sophomores  never
grow up. Like playwright A.R. Gurney. (Reviewed by David L. Beck.)  Through
Dec. 22. San Jose Stage Company. (408) 283-7142.;   Mother Wove the Morning;
(box)Herstory:  16 women given life by Carol Lynn Pearson.  Extended through
Dec. 28. Zephyr Theater, San Francisco. (415) 861-6895.;   La Pastorela;
(box)A medieval shepherd's play,  lovingly adapted by El Teatro Campesino. 
Closes Sunday in Mission San Juan Bautista; Tuesday-Wednesday in St. Joseph
Cathedral, San Jose. (408) 623-2444.;   The Piano Lesson; (box)The wrongs of
slavery  are carved in the veneer of a black family's vintage upright piano by
playwright August Wilson.  Through Jan. 5. ACT at Theater on the Square, San
Francisco. (415) 433-9500.;   Spunk; (box)Three stories  of African-Americans
by Zora Neale Hurston, slickly dramatized by George C. Wolfe.  Through Dec.
21. New York Shakespeare Festival production at Berkeley Rep. (510) 845-4700.;
  Stardust; (box)The songs  of Mitchell Parish (who?) in revue.  Open-ended.
Marines Memorial Theater, San Francisco. (415) 771-6900.;   Taking Steps;
(box)A sex farce  with one joke (albeit a pretty good one) by Alan Ayckbourn. 
Through Jan. 25. ACT at Stage Door Theater, San Francisco. (415) 749-2228.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  -- Judith Green  </BYLINE>
